  "Energy performance, water efficiency, materials sustainability, indoor environmental quality, and site sustainability": "",
  "Only the construction cost per square foot": "",
  "Only the visual appearance and architectural style": "",
  "LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) is a comprehensive green building rating system that evaluates energy performance, water efficiency, materials, indoor environmental quality, and site sustainability across multiple categories.": "",
  "How does passive solar design reduce energy use in buildings?": "",
  "By only insulating the roof of the building": "",
  "By installing solar panels on every available surface": "",
  "By using building orientation, window placement, thermal mass, and insulation to heat and cool naturally": "",
  "By using mechanical heating and cooling systems more efficiently": "",
  "Passive solar design uses architectural strategies, including optimal building orientation, strategic window placement, thermal mass to absorb and release heat, and proper insulation, to naturally regulate indoor temperatures without mechanical systems.": "",
  "What does smart growth urban planning promote?": "",
  "Only tall skyscrapers in downtown areas": "",
  "Compact, walkable, mixed-use communities with public transit access that reduce car dependence and land consumption": "",
  "Low-density suburban development with large lots and wide highways": "",
  "Unlimited expansion of suburban boundaries": "",
  "Smart growth promotes compact, walkable, mixed-use development with good public transit, directing growth toward existing communities rather than sprawling outward, reducing car dependence, land consumption, and infrastructure costs.": "",
  "What causes urban heat islands?": "",
  "Dark pavement and buildings absorbing heat, reduced vegetation, waste heat from energy use, and reduced air flow": "",
  "Cold air masses that get trapped between tall buildings": "",
  "Dense tree canopy that traps heat above the city": "",
  "Only vehicle exhaust emissions warming the air": "",
  "Urban heat islands form because dark surfaces (pavement, rooftops) absorb and re-radiate solar energy, vegetation removal eliminates evaporative cooling, waste heat from buildings and vehicles adds warmth, and building geometry reduces air circulation.": "",
  "How do green roofs help reduce the urban heat island effect?": "",
  "They only add visual appeal to buildings without functional benefits": "",
  "Through evapotranspiration cooling, reflecting sunlight, insulating buildings, and reducing stormwater runoff": "",
  "By blocking wind flow across the building rooftop": "",
  "By only providing habitat for urban wildlife": "",
  "Green roofs provide multiple benefits: plants cool surrounding air through evapotranspiration, vegetation and soil insulate the building, lighter surfaces reflect more sunlight than dark roofs, and soil absorbs rainfall, reducing stormwater runoff.": "",
  "How do bioswales and rain gardens manage stormwater?": "",
  "By channeling all water directly to underground sewer systems": "",
  "By filtering and absorbing runoff through vegetation and soil, reducing flooding and pollutant transport to waterways": "",
  "They serve only as decorative landscaping features": "",
  "They are only effective in dry climates where rainfall is rare": "",
  "Bioswales and rain gardens are green infrastructure features that capture stormwater runoff, filter pollutants through vegetation and engineered soil media, promote infiltration into the ground, and reduce the volume and velocity of water flowing to storm drains.": "",
  "What is transit-oriented development (TOD)?": "",
  "Clustering housing and businesses near public transit stations to reduce car trips, promote walking and biking, and create vibrant mixed-use communities": "",
