  "Building highways directly through city centers for faster commutes": "",
  "Restricting all development to areas within suburban business parks": "",
  "Transit-oriented development concentrates housing, shops, offices, and services within walking distance of transit stations, creating compact, vibrant neighborhoods that reduce car dependence and associated emissions while improving quality of life.": "",
  "Why is urban sprawl considered unsustainable?": "",
  "It is only an aesthetic concern, not an environmental one": "",
  "It consumes farmland and habitat, increases car dependence and emissions, costs more for infrastructure, and fragments wildlife corridors": "",
  "Urban sprawl has no significant environmental downsides": "",
  "It only affects urban areas, not surrounding natural lands": "",
  "Urban sprawl is unsustainable because it converts productive farmland and wildlife habitat, forces car-dependent transportation that increases emissions, raises infrastructure costs for roads, sewers, and utilities, and fragments ecosystems.": "",
  "What is a net-zero energy building?": "",
  "A building that produces as much renewable energy as it consumes annually through on-site generation, efficiency, and design": "",
  "A building that uses no energy whatsoever": "",
  "A building that only operates during daytime hours when solar energy is available": "",
  "A building that is technologically impossible to construct": "",
  "A net-zero energy building produces at least as much renewable energy as it consumes over a year through a combination of high energy efficiency, passive design strategies, and on-site renewable energy generation like rooftop solar.": "",
  "What is low-impact development (LID)?": "",
  "An approach to land development that mimics natural hydrology by managing stormwater at the source through green infrastructure": "",
  "Developing land without any drainage planning": "",
  "Only using piped drainage systems below ground": "",
  "Building only small structures to minimize visual impact": "",
  "Low-impact development uses green infrastructure techniques like permeable pavement, rain gardens, bioswales, and green roofs to manage stormwater at its source, mimicking natural hydrological processes rather than channeling runoff through pipes.": "",
  "What are complete streets?": "",
  "Streets designed for all users: pedestrians, cyclists, public transit riders, and drivers, making them safe and accessible for everyone": "",
  "Streets that connect directly to highway on-ramps": "",
  "Streets that have been fully paved with no remaining gravel sections": "",
  "Streets designed exclusively for automobile traffic with maximum lanes": "",
  "Complete streets are designed and operated to enable safe access for all users, including pedestrians, bicyclists, transit riders, and motorists of all ages and abilities, rather than prioritizing automobile throughput alone.": "",
  "What is embodied carbon in buildings?": "",
  "Only the carbon emissions from operating a building's heating and cooling systems": "",
  "The carbon emissions from manufacturing, transporting, and installing building materials, which are a significant portion of a building's total carbon footprint": "",
  "Only the carbon emissions from demolishing a building": "",
  "Carbon dioxide trapped inside building walls for insulation": "",
  "Embodied carbon refers to the total greenhouse gas emissions generated during the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and installation of building materials. As operational efficiency improves, embodied carbon becomes an increasingly important share of a building's total carbon footprint.": "",
  "What is the 15-minute city concept?": "",
  "A city where the maximum commute time is 15 minutes by car": "",
  "A city with only 15 minutes of public transit service per hour": "",
  "A small town that takes 15 minutes to walk across": "",
  "An urban design where all essential services (shops, schools, healthcare, parks, work) are accessible within a 15-minute walk or bike ride from home": "",
  "The 15-minute city concept envisions urban neighborhoods where residents can access all essential daily services, employment, education, healthcare, shopping, and recreation, within a 15-minute walk or bicycle ride, reducing car dependence.": "",
  "How does permeable pavement reduce environmental impact?": "",
  "It allows rainwater to infiltrate the ground, reducing runoff, recharging groundwater, and filtering pollutants": "",
  "It only works in parking lots and cannot be used for roads": "",
  "It is weaker than conventional pavement and breaks down faster": "",
  "It only looks different from regular pavement but functions identically": "",
  "Permeable pavement allows rainwater to pass through the surface and infiltrate into the ground beneath, reducing stormwater runoff, recharging groundwater aquifers, and filtering pollutants before they reach waterways.": "",
  "What benefits do urban forests and tree canopy provide?": "",
